The paper discusses the use of resistive switching memories (ReRAMs) for Physically Unclonable Functions (PUFs) in cyber-physical security applications. This falls under the category of Emerging Technologies (cs.ET) as ReRAMs are a relatively new technology. The paper also focuses on the security aspect, which suggests it could belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of nano-fabrication and crossbar arrays, which could fall under the categories of Architecture (cs.AR) and Nanoscale Computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the use of Valency Change Mechanism (VCM)-based ReRAM, which is a type of Electrochemical Memory (cs.EM).
